<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-01-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-01-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="655" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to the
                                    <persName type="to">Duke de Arcos</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-01-17"><hi rend="italic">January 17,
                                1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 68.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to advise you that the
                            War Department has received a telegram from General Otis, dated the 15th
                            instant, reporting the troops of General Schwan as east and south of
                            Santo Tomas, Batanzas, and that General Schwan had liberated about 200
                            Spanish prisoners, who, at the date of the telegram, were on the way to
                            Manila.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>